div.div: This is the fill of one of a series of â€˜midden-filledâ€™ pits in Space 329. The other fills are 15753, 15755, 15759, 15761, and 15763, of which the faunal units 15753 and 15755 have already been studied. 15757 is a small unit, similar in size to 15753 and much smaller than 15755. Over 95% of specimens are from sheep/goat or sheep-sized animals. The remainder includes a cattle-sized long bone, two cattle-sized vertebral processes, an equid upper tooth (flot) and humerus shaft fragment, a cattle pelvis fragment and ulna shaft, a pig incisor and thoracic vertebra and a hare femoral head. Finally, there is one specimen each of fish, small bird and micromammal. Dry sieve/handpicked: the main sample is small - perhaps 175 specimens. Amongst the sheep-sized specimens, the scrap:diagnostic balance is roughly even. Long bone shaft fragments are only slightly more abundant than ribs but the usual - for Ã‡atalhÃ¶yÃ¼k - underrepresentation of vertebrae applies (this is not true for cattle-sized animals, although the sample is tiny), and the few recovered are very fragmentary. Ribs are mostly shaft fragments, with no heads and few proximal shafts. Cranial elements are well represented, but most appear to come from a single sheep or goat head, with twin matched maxillae and one mandible nearly complete following refitting. An extra premaxilla and some maxillary fragments raise the sheep-sized cranial MNI to 2, however. The postcranial material is low on feet and heavily biased towards the forelimb, without a single unequivocal sheep-sized hindlimb specimen (although two phalanges could potentially be posterior). This compares with at least three forelimbs from two or more animals (MNE: 1 scapula, 3 humeri, 3 radii, 1 ulna, 2 metacarpals). A pelvis fragment is present, however. Fragmentation is hard to judge given a high frequency of recent breakage (much of which is due to salt crystal formation following excavation) but does not seem to be extreme: modal fragment length is around 40-50mm despite fresh breaks, with several specimens exceeding 100mm. Surface condition is fairly good and quite consistent, with around 90% of specimens at stage 3 (â€˜slight weatheringâ€™) and the remainder at stage 2 (â€˜very slight weatheringâ€™). Colouration is consistent enough to suggest generally similar taphonomic histories (at least for unburnt/undigested bones) but not enough for the material to have derived from a single event. Burning is common, with around 10% of specimens wholly or partially carbonized, and is distributed throughout the postcranial material but not observed on cranial fragments. There are several digested bones (more in the flot - see below), one of which has subsequently become carbonized. No direct signs of butchery are visible and only a few cases of gnawing are evident. Flotation sample #2, >4mm, 100% sorted. The flotation sample contains about three times as many fragments as the main sample, but probably a similar weight of material. It is consistent with the main sample in general appearance and surface condition. While about half of the material consists of indeterminate specimens <20mm in length, the recognisable long bone and rib shaft fragments have a modal length of around 30mm, with many exceeding this despite frequent recent breakage. Long bone shafts are often long, thin splinters. Unsurprisingly, carbonized specimens are slightly more abundant in the flot, making up perhaps 15%. Digested bones are also more common, but nonetheless <5%. Vertebrae are again underrepresented, and rib heads absent, while the overall balance of appendicular:cranial:rib matches the main sample, albeit with many fewer diagnostic long bones. The bias towards sheep-sized forelimbs is not seen in the flot: nothing is added to forelimb MNEs, while three distal tibiae (two digested), two astragali (one digested) and a calcaneus are present from the hindlimb. Feet are, as ever, more common in the flot, although still underrepresented relative to the rest of the limbs in the unit as a whole. Surprisingly, most of the phalanges are undigested. For a midden deposit, the unit is not very diverse, although this may be partly an artefact of small sample size. There is a lack of articulations, but this may simply reflect a paucity of complete articular surfaces in what is after all a small sample. On the other hand, material clearly reached the deposit through several taphonomic pathways, and surface appearance is not especially uniform. Overall, the integrity of the deposit is moderate. The bulk of the material could quite feasibly derive from a small number of animals - perhaps as few as two caprines - and/or a small number of consumption events, with some additional material (the digested and cattle-sized specimens) mixed in. The heavy bias towards forelimbs amongst undigested specimens is interesting in this respect, and may reflect patterned distribution of body parts following initial carcass dismemberment. By comparison with the FUDs from the other studied pit fills in Space 329, 15757 appears more focused than either 15753 or especially the much larger 15755 (although sample size is a factor in the latter case), but still falls broadly within the â€˜middenâ€™ category.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
